537.text: a very old and wrinkled woman

121.text: the power of producing and appreciating

quotes.text: "It was magnificent,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Do you remember what Darwin says about music? He claims that the power of producing and appreciating it existed among the human race long before the power of speech was arrived at. Perhaps that is why we are so subtly influenced by it. There are vague memories in our souls of those misty centuries when the world was in its childhood."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "That's rather a broad idea,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "One's ideas must be as broad as Nature if they are to interpret Nature,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "What's the matter? You're not looking quite yourself. This Brixton Road affair has upset you."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "To tell the truth, it has,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I ought to be more case-hardened after my Afghan experiences. I saw my own comrades hacked to pieces at Maiwand without losing my nerve."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I can understand. There is a mystery about this which stimulates the imagination; where there is no imagination there is no horror. Have you seen the evening paper?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "No."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "It gives a fairly good account of the affair. It does not mention the fact that when the man was raised up, a woman's wedding ring fell upon the floor. It is just as well it does not."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Why?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Look at this advertisement,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I had one sent to every paper this morning immediately after the affair."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Found"
quotes.speaker: Watson

quotes.text: "In Brixton Road, this morning,"
quotes.speaker: Watson

quotes.text: "a plain gold wedding ring, found in the roadway between the 'White Hart' Tavern and Holland Grove. Apply Dr. Watson, 221b, Baker Street, between eight and nine this evening."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Excuse my using your name,"
quotes.speaker: Watson

quotes.text: "If I used my own some of these dunderheads would recognize it, and want to meddle in the affair."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "That is all right,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "But supposing anyone applies, I have no ring."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Oh yes, you have,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "This will do very well. It is almost a facsimile."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "And who do you expect will answer this advertisement."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Why, the man in the brown coat--our florid friend with the square toes. If he does not come himself he will send an accomplice."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Would he not consider it as too dangerous?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Not at all. If my view of the case is correct, and I have every reason to believe that it is, this man would rather risk anything than lose the ring. According to my notion he dropped it while stooping over Drebber's body, and did not miss it at the time. After leaving the house he discovered his loss and hurried back, but found the police already in possession, owing to his own folly in leaving the candle burning. He had to pretend to be drunk in order to allay the suspicions which might have been aroused by his appearance at the gate. Now put yourself in that man's place. On thinking the matter over, it must have occurred to him that it was possible that he had lost the ring in the road after leaving the house. What would he do, then? He would eagerly look out for the evening papers in the hope of seeing it among the articles found. His eye, of course, would light upon this. He would be overjoyed. Why should he fear a trap? There would be no reason in his eyes why the finding of the ring should be connected with the murder. He would come. He will come. You shall see him within an hour."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "And then?"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Oh, you can leave me to deal with him then. Have you any arms?"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "I have my old service revolver and a few cartridges."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "You had better clean it and load it. He will be a desperate man, and though I shall take him unawares, it is as well to be ready for anything."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "The plot thickens,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "I have just had an answer to my American telegram. My view of the case is the correct one."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "And that is?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "My fiddle would be the better for new strings,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Put your pistol in your pocket. When the fellow comes speak to him in an ordinary way. Leave the rest to me. Don't frighten him by looking at him too hard."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "It is eight o'clock now,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Yes. He will probably be here in a few minutes. Open the door slightly. That will do. Now put the key on the inside. Thank you! This is a queer old book I picked up at a stall yesterday--De Jure inter Gentes--published in Latin at Liege in the Lowlands, in 1642. Charles' head was still firm on his shoulders when this little brown-backed volume was struck off."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Who is the printer?"
quotes.speaker: Charles

quotes.text: "Philippe de Croy, whoever he may have been. On the fly-leaf, in very faded ink, is written 'Ex libris Guliolmi Whyte.' I wonder who William Whyte was. Some pragmatical seventeenth century lawyer, I suppose. His writing has a legal twist about it. Here comes our man, I think."
quotes.speaker: Charles

quotes.text: "Does Dr. Watson live here?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Come in,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "It's this as has brought me, good gentlemen,"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "a gold wedding ring in the Brixton Road. It belongs to my girl Sally, as was married only this time twelvemonth, which her husband is steward aboard a Union boat, and what he'd say if he comes 'ome and found her without her ring is more than I can think, he being short enough at the best o' times, but more especially when he has the drink. If it please you, she went to the circus last night along with--"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "Is that her ring?"
quotes.speaker: Houndsditch

quotes.text: "The Lord be thanked!"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "Sally will be a glad woman this night. That's the ring."
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "And what may your address be?"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "13, Duncan Street, Houndsditch. A weary way from here."
quotes.speaker: Sherlock Holmes

quotes.text: "The Brixton Road does not lie between any circus and Houndsditch,"
quotes.speaker: Sherlock Holmes

quotes.text: "The gentleman asked me for my address,"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "Sally lives in lodgings at 3, Mayfield Place, Peckham."
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "And your name is--?"
quotes.speaker: Peckham

quotes.text: "My name is Sawyer--her's is Dennis, which Tom Dennis married her--and a smart, clean lad, too, as long as he's at sea, and no steward in the company more thought of; but when on shore, what with the women and what with liquor shops--"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "Here is your ring, Mrs. Sawyer,"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "it clearly belongs to your daughter, and I am glad to be able to restore it to the rightful owner."
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "I'll follow her,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "she must be an accomplice, and will lead me to him. Wait up for me."
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "Either his whole theory is incorrect,"
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "or else he will be led now to the heart of the mystery."
quotes.speaker: her

quotes.text: "I wouldn't have the Scotland Yarders know it for the world,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I have chaffed them so much that they would never have let me hear the end of it. I can afford to laugh, because I know that I will be even with them in the long run."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "What is it then?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Oh, I don't mind telling a story against myself. That creature had gone a little way when she began to limp and show every sign of being foot-sore. Presently she came to a halt, and hailed a four-wheeler which was passing. I managed to be close to her so as to hear the address, but I need not have been so anxious, for she sang it out loud enough to be heard at the other side of the street, 'Drive to 13, Duncan Street, Houndsditch,' she cried. This begins to look genuine, I thought, and having seen her safely inside, I perched myself behind. That's an art which every detective should be an expert at. Well, away we rattled, and never drew rein until we reached the street in question. I hopped off before we came to the door, and strolled down the street in an easy, lounging way. I saw the cab pull up. The driver jumped down, and I saw him open the door and stand expectantly. Nothing came out though. When I reached him he was groping about frantically in the empty cab, and giving vent to the finest assorted collection of oaths that ever I listened to. There was no sign or trace of his passenger, and I fear it will be some time before he gets his fare. On inquiring at Number 13 we found that the house belonged to a respectable paperhanger, named Keswick, and that no one of the name either of Sawyer or Dennis had ever been heard of there."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "You don't mean to say,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "that that tottering, feeble old woman was able to get out of the cab while it was in motion, without either you or the driver seeing her?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Old woman be damned!"
quotes.speaker: Sherlock Holmes

quotes.text: "We were the old women to be so taken in. It must have been a young man, and an active one, too, besides being an incomparable actor. The get-up was inimitable. He saw that he was followed, no doubt, and used this means of giving me the slip. It shows that the man we are after is not as lonely as I imagined he was, but has friends who are ready to risk something for him. Now, Doctor, you are looking done-up. Take my advice and turn in."
quotes.speaker: Sherlock Holmes
